# Gmail Filter Manager

A Google Apps Script that creates and manages Gmail filters — applying labels, skipping the inbox, and marking emails as important. Managed through a web app UI, with filter data stored in a Google Sheet as the source of truth.

---

## Features

- **Web app UI** — add filters from any browser without opening the Apps Script editor
- **Sheet-based storage** — all filter entries live in a Google Sheet; add rows directly to the sheet to define filters without using the UI
- **Auto-creates labels** — including nested labels like `Finance/Alerts`
- **Skips duplicates** — if an identical filter already exists in Gmail, it won't create another
- **Replaces outdated filters** — if a filter exists for the same sender but with different settings, deletes the old one and creates the updated one
- **Backfill on demand** — filters added through the web UI apply the label to existing matching threads; filters added directly to the sheet do not backfill
- **PropertiesService cache** — label IDs and filter criteria are cached locally so repeat syncs skip Gmail API calls for entries that haven't changed

---

## Setup

### 1. Create a new Apps Script project
Go to [script.google.com](https://script.google.com) and create a new standalone project.

### 2. Enable the Gmail API advanced service
- In the left sidebar, click **Services** (`+`)
- Find **Gmail API** and click **Add**

### 3. Create the files
Delete the default `Code.gs` and create the following files, pasting in the contents of each:

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `Main.gs` | Entry points: `doGet()` and `syncFilters()` |
| `Helpers.gs` | Gmail label and filter logic; PropertiesService cache functions |
| `Spreadsheet.gs` | All Google Sheet read/write operations |
| `Index.html` | The web app UI |

### 4. Initialize the sheet
Run `getOrCreateSheet()` once from the editor. This creates the "Gmail Filter Manager" spreadsheet in your Drive and sets up the Filters sheet with proper formatting.

### 5. Deploy as a web app
- Go to **Deploy → New deployment**
- Click the gear icon next to "Select type" and choose **Web app**
- Set **Execute as** to `Me`
- Set **Who has access** to `Only myself`
- Click **Deploy** and copy the URL

Bookmark that URL — it's your permanent entry point. The spreadsheet runs in the background as storage; you don't need to open it directly.

### 6. Authorize the script
On first run you'll be prompted to authorize the script to access Gmail and Drive. Follow the prompts.

---

## Usage

### Adding filters via the web app

Open your bookmarked web app URL. On the **Add Filters** tab, enter one filter per line:

```html
email@example.com, Label Name
email@example.com, Label Name, skipInbox, markImportant
```

- The label will be created in Gmail if it doesn't exist yet
- Existing threads from that sender will be labeled and archived (if `skipInbox` is `true`)

| Field | Type | Description | Default | Required |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `email@example.com` | string | The sender's email address | N/A | Yes |
| `Label Name` | string | The label to apply, created automatically if it doesn't exist | N/A | Yes |
| `skipInbox` | boolean | `true` to archive, `false` to keep in inbox | `false` | No |
| `markImportant` | boolean | `true` to mark as important, `false` to leave as-is | `false` | No |

**Note:** Fields are comma-separated. Omit optional boolean fields to use their defaults. For example:

```html
<!-- both booleans default to false -->
dad@family.com, Social 

<!-- — skipInbox is false, markImportant is true -->
boss@work.com, Work, false, true 
```

### Adding filters directly to the sheet

Open the "Gmail Filter Manager" spreadsheet in Drive and add rows manually:

| Email | Label | Skip Inbox | Mark Important | Last Synced |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| alerts@service.com | Newsletters | ✓ | ☐ | |

Then run `syncFilters()` from the Apps Script editor. Filters added this way are **not backfilled** — the label will only apply to new incoming emails, not existing threads.

### Viewing existing filters

The **View Filters** tab in the web app shows all entries currently in the sheet, including their settings and last sync time.

### Syncing the sheet to Gmail

`syncFilters()` reads every row in the sheet and ensures a matching Gmail label and filter exists for each one. Safe to run repeatedly — entries that are already in sync are skipped. Run this any time you add rows directly to the sheet.

---

## Entry points

### `doGet()`
Serves the web app UI. Called automatically when someone visits the deployment URL — you never run this directly.

### `syncFilters()`
The only function you run manually from the Apps Script editor (after initial setup). Reads all rows from the sheet and applies any filters not yet in Gmail. Does not backfill existing emails.

---

## File structure

### `Main.gs`
Contains the two entry points and the core filter logic:
- `doGet()` — serves `Index.html` as the web app
- `syncFilters()` — syncs all sheet rows to Gmail
- `addFiltersFromUI(rawInput)` — called by the web UI via `google.script.run`; parses input, creates filters, and backfills existing threads
- `getFiltersForUI()` — called by the web UI to populate the View Filters table
- `applyFilter(email, labelName, skipInbox, markImportant, backfill)` — creates a Gmail label and filter for one address; shared by both `addFiltersFromUI` and `syncFilters`

### `Helpers.gs`
Gmail API logic and the PropertiesService cache:
- `getOrCreateLabel(labelName)` — returns a label's ID, creating it if needed; cache-first
- `processExistingFilters(from, labelId, skipInbox, markImportant)` — checks for existing Gmail filters; cache-first; keeps exact matches, deletes outdated ones
- `isDesiredFilter(match, labelId, skipInbox, markImportant)` — compares a filter object against desired criteria
- `cacheFilter / getCachedFilter / evictFilterCache` — PropertiesService helpers for filter criteria
- `cacheLabelId / getCachedLabelId` — PropertiesService helpers for label IDs
- `parseBool(val, defaultValue)` — parses `"true"`/`"false"` strings as booleans

### `Spreadsheet.gs`
All sheet access — no Gmail logic lives here:
- `getOrCreateSpreadsheet()` — finds or creates the "Gmail Filter Manager" spreadsheet; caches its ID
- `getOrCreateSheet()` — finds or creates the Filters sheet with header and formatting
- `readFiltersFromSheet()` — returns all data rows as an array of objects
- `writeFilterToSheet(email, labelName, skipInbox, markImportant)` — appends a new row with checkbox formatting; skips duplicates
- `markSyncedInSheet(email)` — updates the Last Synced timestamp for a given row
- `filterExistsInSheet(email)` — returns true if a row with that email already exists

### `Index.html`
The web app UI. Two tabs:
- **Add Filters** — textarea input with client-side validation, loading state, and a color-coded results log
- **View Filters** — table of all entries from the sheet

---

## Notes

- The Gmail API returns filters under `response.filter` (singular) — this is an API quirk, not a typo.
- Built-in Gmail label IDs (`"INBOX"`, `"IMPORTANT"`) are always uppercase.
- Nested labels use `/` as a separator (e.g. `Job Search/In Progress`) and appear as a folder hierarchy in the Gmail sidebar.
- `GmailApp.search()` returns a maximum of 500 threads. If you have more than 500 emails from one sender, the backfill will only label the first 500.
- When you make code changes, redeploy via **Deploy → Manage deployments → Edit** and increment the version. The URL stays the same.